50|$|There were {{approximately}} 85 million <b>rice</b> <b>cookers</b> made in 2005. Most of the <b>rice</b> <b>cookers</b> {{were made in}} China, South Korea and Japan, with 70% of the production in China. Most of Chinese production was from Zhanjiang City and Lianjiang City in Guangdong Province.|$|R
50|$|Because {{the cooking}} {{temperature}} of modern electric <b>rice</b> <b>cookers</b> is precisely controlled, okoge does not usually form naturally during the cooking process. However, there are <b>rice</b> <b>cookers</b> {{on the market}} in Japan that have an okoge setting. Okoge can also be made by scorching cooked rice in a frying pan.|$|R
